  "definition": {
    "en": "Pentoxyverine Citrate, when dried, contains not less than 98."
  },
  "appearance": {
    "en": "Pentoxyverine Citrate occurs as a white crys-talline powder. It is very soluble in acetic acid (100), freely soluble in water and in ethanol (95), and practically insoluble in diethyl ether."
  },
  "testSpecification": [
    {
      "@type": "IdentificationSpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Identification"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Identification",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "(1) Dissolve 0.1 g of Pentoxyverine Citrate in 10 mL of water, and add 10 mL of Reinecke salt TS: a light red precipitate is formed. Determine the infrared absorption spectrum of Pen- ‌toxyverine Citrate, previously dried, as directed in the paste method under Infrared Spectrophotometry <2.25>, and com-pare the spectrum with the Reference Spectrum: both spectra exhibit similar intensities of absorption at the same wave numbers. A solution of Pentoxyverine Citrate (1 in 10) re-sponds to Qualitative Tests <1.09> (1) and (2) for citrate."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "PuritySpecification",
      "testName": {
        "en": "Purity"
      },
      "testType": "TestType-Purity",
      "testConditions": {
        "en": "(1) Clarity and color of solution—Dissolve 1.0 g of Pentoxyverine Citrate in 10 mL of water: the solution is clear and colorless. Heavy metals <1.07>—Proceed with 2.0 g of Pentox- yverine Citrate according to Method 2, and perform the test. Prepare the control solution with 2.0 mL of Standard Lead Solution (not more than 10 ppm). Arsenic <1.11>—Prepare the test solution with 1.0 g of Pentoxyverine Citrate according to Method 3, and per-form the test (not more than 2 ppm). Peplomycin Sulfate"
      }
    }
  ]
}